verified.integration_reality:
Split verdict by package:

@medplum/fhirtypes: Clean. Zero dependencies, pure type-only devDependency. Drop-in alongside TypeSpec-emitted contracts; fhirtypes covers R4 resource shapes TypeSpec does not natively emit. No Bun/NestJS friction. Ponytail ladder check: @types/fhir (DefinitelyTyped) is the stdlib-tier alternative - it exists, is actively published (0.0.44, June 2026), but has known open defects (circular reference in FhirResource, missing SimpleQuantity/MoneyQuantity types per open DT issues). @medplum/fhirtypes is materially more complete, actively co-evolved with the client, and already versioned as a unit. @types/fhir does NOT cover this adequately; @medplum/fhirtypes earns its place.

@medplum/core: Socket.dev confirmed "no external dependencies" - the React peer-dep risk in the candidate card is overstated. React lives in @medplum/react, not @medplum/core. MedplumClient accepts a custom fetch implementation via MedplumClientOptions.fetch, making it Bun-compatible (Bun implements WHATWG fetch). NestJS injection as a provider is straightforward (constructor injection, no framework coupling in the lib). Zod wrapping of fhirtypes for runtime validation is additive and generator-friendly. Generator-first alignment: @curaos/fhir-client wraps MedplumClient - the generator emits the wrapper, not the client itself; upgrade path is a single dep bump. RISK: v5 requires Node 22+ / Bun equivalent; v5 is ESM-only. Bun handles ESM natively; NestJS 11 with ESM needs explicit tsconfig + package.json type:module configuration - non-trivial but documented. This is the real integration effort, not React.

@medplum/fhirpath: Standalone, no server dependency. Useful for declarative patient-compartment queries. Lower priority than the other two; evaluate in Trial phase, not Day 1.

Lock-in analysis: MedplumClient is a thin FHIR HTTP client - switching to a different FHIR client (hapi-fhir-js, fhir.js) requires replacing one class in @curaos/fhir-client, not rewriting consumers. Generator-first wrapper insulates from upstream churn. No lock-in beyond the type layer, which is R4-standard anyway.

R5 gap: Medplum paused R5 intentionally (US regulators signaled R6 will be the next US Core base, skipping R5). CuraOS HealthStack is US Core / USCDI aligned; this is a non-issue for v1. R6 path exists - Medplum tracks it. Acceptable risk.

ESM-in-NestJS is the real friction: NestJS 11 + Bun + ESM-only dep requires "type":"module" in package.json or per-package esm config in tsconfig paths. This is a known pattern but adds ~half-sprint of glue to the initial @curaos/fhir-client scaffold. Not a rejection signal, but the effort estimate of S in the candidate card is optimistic; realistic effort is M for the first package, S for subsequent healthstack consumers once the template is proven.
